The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our service providers offer practically the same services as their Western European partners.
Despite this, we lack something here - a virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be much longer.
We have already written on Mobil.cz that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was confirmed by the “TOUR”, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than that of the other countries of the Union.
After the recent move of the European Commission, this may lead to a controversial situation in order to regulate roaming charges – some of the customers of Czech mobile operators’ text messages will be cheaper than the domestic ones.
How is it possible that the prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, as we have three mobile networks and our penetration is far above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvorak, the president of the Czech Telecommunications Office Council, also agrees with this, who has previously stated a few times that there is no room for another service provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic service provider probably doesn’t have a lot of chances with its own network (in all, it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
But there is one more option - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought a significant price decrease, and then the classic service providers had to react.
Meanwhile, even before the big fish entered the market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in Great Britain, sounds similar to ours were heard.
However, it has been proven that such service providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, for example, we don’t have to go too far.
In February this year we informed you about the launch of Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
In less than half a year, this service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
To operate efficiently, you need far fewer customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not entail relatively high construction and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world generally appear as low-cost ones - they offer cheap calls and text messages, which is often offset by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers text messages that are at least 50 percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it is quite a good move to bet on a target group.
This service provider focuses on men.
“True men choose Mobilking – who they like, who they can trust,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual service provider.
It is hard to say whether an idea similar to that of Poland can work in Hungary.
A spokesperson for Vodafone, Miroslav, a spokesperson for Vodafone, doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which the majority of virtual service providers are based.
It is also relatively satisfied in terms of the supply of services."
There is no chance in the Czech Republic, according to mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem to be too hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region,” Jana Studnisková, spokeswoman for the Financial Group, told Mobil.cz.
This indirectly demonstrated that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competition can be achieved.
The GTS Novera Group has not been a secret for some time to keep its interest in launching a virtual service provider, which aims to take another step to make Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in providing our customers not only with fixed line, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe it's better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual service provider is lucky by the end of the year.
His birth, however, is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At this moment, we do not think that a full-fledged virtual service provider has a place in the Czech market.
Unlike other markets, the Czech market is very special.
So far, we have not been addressed by an uneven subject, which offers complex and serious projects in this field,” Vlastimil Sr?e?, the press department of Telefónica 02, told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokeswoman for T-Mobile, said: “Until now, we have not recorded any viable and bilaterally beneficial business projects on which we could be based on it.”
And he added: “Study on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual provider will appear.
At the moment, we should have a concrete agreement on our table so that it can be thought so short-term.”
Vodafone’s attention is more focused on fulfilling its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav adds: "We are open to negotiating with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is exactly what we consider to be the most paying for customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy is to partner in this area to build networks shared for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - on one string with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another service provider would mean an increase in competition, leading to a price decrease and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When it comes to service providers, they are able to cooperate, the struggle around the birth of the U:fon is also testifying.
The biggest pressure on the T-Mobile company’s U:fon is probably about the birth of the U:fon of T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the website of the “TION”.
But right now, the U:fon comes in handy as a good argument as a reason why we shouldn’t allow the virtual provider to log in.
Martina Kemrová added: “The environment of the mobile market competition has recently been unravelled by the market of the fourth mobile operator’s market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would be high in the market and its services."
However, given such attitudes by mobile operators, the total disinterest of the Czech regulators is astonishing.
In the meantime, it is not only about the attitude of the “TOUR”, which, unfortunately, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has no right to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
Only the Hungarian Competition Authority is entitled to do so.
But the office has a characteristic attitude towards the whole problem.
“The virtual service provider’s mobile market could only be concluded after a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual service provider on the leasing of the necessary infrastructure would be concluded.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for traditional service providers,” said Kristián Chlapua, the Foreign Relations Department of the Hungarian Competition Authority.
A statement from the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office that should represent the interests of consumers and make sure that no one can abuse its market position, this is more than strange.
Especially if Kristián Chalupa adds: “In the outskirts where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the price of mobile phone services.”
It is likely, however, that the pressure on the market environment and the decrease in prices is not presumably in the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, the resilience of the three mobile operators is indeed shocking.
The question is whether it is only a coincidence, it is almost self-evident.
Just like the completely identical gasoline prices at the filling stations are just the work of chance and hard competition.
“The Office did not discover signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers have a leading position, i.e. they have no proportionately greater responsibility for their market activities.
The tools necessary for the opening of the mobile market of virtual service providers are likely to be missing for the telecoms regulator,” said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leader situation is one of the many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the TUR, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
After that, of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has a monopoly on its own network, relatively logically.
So, in a certain segment, it is necessarily dominant.
But even if we didn’t accept this argument, ÚOHS would have to be at least a warning that three mobile operators are acting remarkably similarly.
Meanwhile, complaints from the inquirers (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that there are very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the TUR is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which the ÚOHS takes its hands off the whole case.
We have seen this in some similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunication Act, the extension of the powers of the scope of the “TION in the field of economic competition” in the telecommunications industry could not be carried out, although many experts hoped for an improvement in the situation.
Representatives of the ÚOHS need to know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one is watching
Meanwhile, the operation of some pseudo-virtual service providers will be unnoticed, of which many of them already operate in the mobile networks of the Czech Republic.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, which, however, are only partially public.
They are multi-level marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer in the face of the service provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a privileged customer, you will then receive special quotations (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-sales.
“If there were cases that you are talking about, the terms of the terms that we would be dealing with, and which could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with the company concerned,” Martina Kemrová said in response to a question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that the news of such activity did not reach the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, the three companies mentioned above may be thousands of customers.
In the meantime, no service provider is defending itself against such a procedure.
They have not insignificant profits from the activities of these companies, and they do not pose a particular threat to their own official marketing, unlike real virtual service providers.
Miroslav “epick” warns of possible problems: “The law allows similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that their phone does not contain the SIM card in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as generic customers of mobile operators.”
But that's what the Way should be at least strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why do they hinder the birth of the virtual service provider?
It should be added that ÚOHS has relatively strong powers to expose such activity, and if you do not want to, you do not have to be content with the service providers’ explanation that they did not suspect anything of this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers to the mobile market has resulted in a noticeable decrease in the prices of services.
Meanwhile, in practically all countries where virtual service providers were established, the classic service providers tried to prevent their creation more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - a market that was too small, possibly too satisfied, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was precisely at this very moment that the regulatory bodies intervened, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Then, with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual service provider that others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators are serving the whole case with each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competencies come in handy for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider will be available to us soon, the Czech mobile market may be in motion again.
If a service provider would allow the establishment of a virtual mobile operator, ÚOHS would be difficult to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may not be going to make any more expensive calls.
