The collision-avoidant "bee car"
This time, Nissan drew inspiration from nature, the world of bees, to the development of accident-preventive technologies.
The Japanese company has designed a robot that avoids accidents mimic the bee flight.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in developing collision-preventive technologies.
The Nissan Motor Co. Engineers from the Advanced Technical Centre of the renowned Tokyo University, in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Centre of the renowned University of Tokyo, built this little robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Director of the Technology Public Relations and Research and Development Brand, is defined as the BR23C as an additional extension of Nissan’s four-level safety guard cover.
The robot makes the company’s ability to avoid collision.
During flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety guard cover.
More importantly, the role of the uterus is more important in the complex eye of the uterus, with which you see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees. Consequently, the uterus can fly undisturbed in its own personal space.
To replicate the complex eye function, engineers designed a so-called laser rangefinder (Laser Range Finder).
The instrument identifies obstacles in a 180-degree field of vision in front of the BR23C within a distance of up to 2 meters, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into an operation to avoid a collision.
“As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot, immeiting the movement of the uterus, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid a collision.
What distinguishes the system from the currently available instruments is that in this case the bypass maneuver is completely automatic.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer for the project.
Unlike bees, the detour can not be directed up or downwards, nor diagonally, moving only in two dimensions and only in the direction of the swirling of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and manner, as in the case of bees.
That’s why Nissan used a rotational function in the robot in addition to accelerating and deceleration to avoid collisions.
“This device has to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need to store data, nor intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvres, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it's not gigabytes, but we don't even talk about megabyte memories.
This is the first step in developing an instant collision prevention technology that Nissan estimates to enter production cars within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the combination of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could provide further application to the end goal by avoiding obstacles on the road.
Retired drunk drivers will be forced to install the "Alcolock"
After three drunk driving offences, the Ministry of Interior would force the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from starting the vehicle if the driver was drunk or not blowing into the device.
The proposal was presented in June and is currently being dealt with by the State Prosecutor’s Office, according to which the pilot project will last for one year.
Since the purpose of the project is to restore traffic, the driver will also have to take part in a repeating course on transport education.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor’s Office, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Car Safety Technology Foundation (FITSA) are also involved in the experiment.
According to statistics, 30-75 percent of motorists who have been arrested for drunk driving are back in the car again.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air blown into it. If it is greater than the permissible, or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the car to start.
The cost of the instrument of more than 1000 euros would be borne by the offender.
A 2007 study in the U.S. found that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that this rule could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure focuses on violations for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from becoming a criminal offence,
On the other hand, it is easier to introduce it, as the implementation of the legal reform is carried out in the usual way, while the necessary criminal reform would require an amendment to the Fundamental Law.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers’ Party to include the system in school buses, as a French model.
