Those who speak in their dreams
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean those who wake up and tell them what happened to them that day, but those who speak while they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem frightening at first, but it is actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquismus.
Quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure they've told some of them he was talking at night.
It can be completely rhapsodic (for example, it occurs only once with a high fever) or more regular (daily, weekly or once a month), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single trigger.
It is often coupled with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, nighttime urination, and evening urination (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal either.
As already mentioned, it can be a high-flying condition, or even a stressful situation or an increased agitation.
So far, little has been studied.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, it can consist of incoherent words, murmurs, but, unlike all this, it may also occur in the form of shouting, crying or speaking for a longer period.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and to consult a specialist. The examination can reveal whether there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and can offer a solution.
As already mentioned, it is a benign phenomenon, and consequently there is no cure for it, unless the sleep disorder is associated with some other manageable form (such as insomnia or stressful situation).
However, there are a few things we can do, here is a set of preventive measures:
Be careful that the child stays calm before going to bed.
Choose reassuring games and avoid watching your child’s fear-mongering or more aggressive TV shows or series.
Children who are prone to nervousness or have a harder time relaxing will be taught to find some relaxation methods to find inner calm.
This helps the child to sleep more peacefully.
If you do start talking during your sleep, try to keep your peace.
Remember, it is harmless to the child, and they won’t remember anything the next day.
Useful advice
Don't wake the child up.
It would be superfluous because the child is unconscious, but he would get out of sleep.
Even though he talks, he actually continues to sleep and rest.
Remember, if the phenomenon is accompanied by severe anxiety several times, it is advisable to consult a specialist or to reveal what causes the child to have a high degree of anxiety.
