Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday. Dr. Dr. President Francine Décary had a good reason to celebrate, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world.
Most importantly, it managed to regain the trust of the people, which seriously shattered by the 1980s and 1990s’ Incredible Blood-related scandal.
As it is known, the blood supply service of the Canadian Red Cross was treated by the national blood supply reserve of the acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general upheaval, the government of Canada, in February 1994, under the leadership of Judge Horace Krever, launched an official investigation. The purpose of this was to shed light on the circumstances led to the tragedy and to make suggestions to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed the submission of his report, some provinces set up their own committee to design a new blood management system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee held this task.
The Gélineau and Krever reports led to the creation of two blood supply services in Canada: the Hema-Québec serving Quebec, and the other is the other of the other provinces and the Canadian Blood Transfusion Company responsible for the supply of the two territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activity in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Quebec’s blood supply system,” recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
“In the years that followed, we have regained people’s trust as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field.” Décary is proud to announce that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population considered the Héma-Québece to be reliable.
However, Dr. Decary does not forget that “trust is an extremely fragile thing”.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, the Hema-Québec has used the principle of prudence.
During this period, a number of cases have been revealed in Europe where a new variant of mad cow disease, i.e. Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, has also infected people, says the doctor, who has been in charge of the company since its founding in 1998.
“We had no idea whether this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. Accordingly, if we are unsure and there is a risk of developing a serious illness, we must use exclusion measures. In this case, it was a Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that causes brain changes, so it inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999, we did not accept blood from people who have spent more than a month in the UK since 1980.
A few years ago, it was clear that the disease was spread through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the principle of prudence.”
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that allows the HIV virus to be more sensitively diagnosed. This nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, not antibodies against the virus, on which the previously used tests were built.
With the help of the NAT test, we could shorten the window period, which lasts from infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with the help of our technical devices, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to a period of less than a week.
Thus, they significantly reduced the risk that blood donors were unknowingly infecting blood and not detecting it.
These developments have greatly reduced the risk of spreading AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
“Other things put, that means we should allocate 12 million blood products while someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 4000,000 and 500,000 blood products every year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to become infected with HIV through a blood product.
“I think anyone can accept or prescribe blood transfusions in order to restore health,” says the chief executive of Héma-Québec.
“The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what kind of new pathogens will enter the system.
It was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood with insect bites.
Therefore, we must be constantly on our guard,” Dr. Décary continued, stressing that in addition to emergency reserves, Héma-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
“With the ageing of the population, the demand is increasing.
Because anticancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the population of blood donors, as the number of people in the network for blood donation accounts for only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, all healthy people, at least 18 years old, who meet the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example. Those who have been to a country where malaria is destroying is not entitled to blood donation for a year.
“With this, we have the 3% of the reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It is very rare to run out of stocks.
However, we have to increase the number of blood donors as much as the existing ones get older, because after a while they can no longer donate blood.
But it is very difficult for people to be persuaded to give blood, but it is even more difficult to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In this fast-paced world today, you barely have a single hour to go to give blood,” says Francine Décary.
The Hema-Québec, who has an annual budget of USD 297 million, provides not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeball tissues and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severely burned people.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen, and then placed at the Hema-Québec, which also treats Quebec’s only public stem cell bank.
The umbilical cord, which was once treated as medical waste, can extract blood that is rich in stem cells, allowing for the treatment of serious diseases (such as leukemia).
“We celebrated a few weeks ago that the thousandth umbilical cord blood sample was added to our bank, and we plan to remove more than a thousand new samples every year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them for organ transplants,” said Dr. Décary, who believes that the umbilical cord blood removal program is very popular nowadays.
“Many moms are sad that you don’t have the chance to do so,” really is the case, because Héma-Québec is not in a position to make this complex and costly program available in all hospitals in Quebec.
