The Orwellian speech of Barrick Gold
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter was published by Patrick J. Garver, deputy CEO of the mine Barrick Gold of Canada.
Following Orwelli’s exposition, Garver states that the world’s largest gold-producing company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small-money publishing company to initiate a so-called “public debate.”
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decision, especially in defamation lawsuits, is made not on the basis of the truth, but by law.
It's no surprise that Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to do public debate would be to destroy anyone whose position is contrary to his?
Irrespective of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada will have to spend significant amounts of money on defense and combat in an unequal struggle where on the other hand is an army of lawyers backed by almost inexhaustible sources of the mining industry.
In such an unequal struggle, by the way, the tactics of destroying the defendant and making a friendly agreement, which not only silences the opposite, but also intimidates those who would try to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he should have expressed his views in public opinion.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold is active, this is done differently, in Canada, the parties that are disputing usually do not hit each other with a stick, but tell their thoughts.
Therefore, it would have been enough for the mine to open its books and dossiers and prepare for a real debate in the press, media and publications, paying for independent research groups that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to trust public opinion, and one move will sweep aside the petitions and letters written to the authors of Noir Canada.
Can Mr Garver explain to you how to initiate a "public" debate if, at the same time, disregards the opinion of this public?
In the head of the vice-president, this word probably means only lawyers who have paid me generously, not Canada’s total population: the meaning of the term is thus greatly narrow.
In a democratic state, even those who defame others are entitled to freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand – or does not want to understand – that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are mainly supported by the public because it condemns the rough procedure of the mine.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and make a judgment, but it would do so on the basis of civilized arguments, not by a lawsuit aimed at silencing many. (In the context of the term "public debate," Barrick Gold recently called on the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using that term.)
In addition to Garver’s surreal statements, Barrick Gold’s process poses an open attack on the freedom of university research and the search for justice, which are the building blocks of all democratic societies.
The procedure, taken as a whole, denies the right to quote credible sources, and the right to debate facts and their interpretation, which form the basis of intellectual activities.
If a country like Canada can only be studied and discuss topics under the burden of litigation that you do not like the rich companies of today’s world, then who will dare to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted an open and transparent debate, it could do so according to the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada apply.
You have the right to answer.
We have been able to deal with debates, differences and conflict in our university for a long time.
Barrick Gold’s ill-considered procedure shows that, contrary to its claim, it did not want to have an open debate.
This is a loss for both the world of universities and the institution of public debate in Canada. It is time for governments to finally implement measures to limit legal proceedings for such abuse.
Wall Street Rescue: Democrats and Republicans agree
Yesterday, the Bush administration and the Republican and Democratic leaders of the Congress finally reached an agreement on the economic rescue operation, which is the largest such plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The plan, worth 700 billion US dollars, to curb the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months, still needs to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
Substantive points of the plan: more effective control of implementation by Members; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the state funds allocated; new provisions to maintain the number of houses seized due to non-payment; the right of access to the salaries of the managers of companies benefiting from the salaries.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Nancy Pelosi, President of the U.S. House of Representatives, and Judd Gregg, Republican MP who was in the trial, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon trial ended.
“We have made a big step forward towards a solution that will work effectively in the markets,” said Henry Paulson, a representative of the Bush administration.
“We did everything with the aim of saving the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis that hit Wall Street,” he said.
“The most important aspect is that if we don’t do that, there will be a huge shock, chaos and confusion in the everyday life of Americans,” said Republican Congressman Judd Gregg.
The trial was accelerated in the last few hours, fearing that another failure would have a detrimental effect on investors’ mood.
They gave themselves a deadline for the agreement until the opening of the stock market this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late were ready to reach an agreement, but they were not happy that the situation had increased to the end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the expansion of the agreement with elements such as the provisions on the preservation of house ownership or the salaries of the leaders of companies that have been helped by the state.
“When we ask taxpayers to take some extraordinary steps to take some extraordinary action because of other people’s irresponsibility, it’s not a welcome thing.
These steps are necessary,” he said in an American television show.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied, “I want to know the details, but I hope they do.”
“What I have read broadly, it can be seen that it is something that we all need to digest and by which we can move forward.
“The possibility of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,” he said.
According to the 700-billion-dollar plan, taxpayers’ money would be used to buy the dubious claims of American financial institutions, and some risky, unsellable assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis triggered by the bursting of the real estate bubble. This first led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgages), then spread to other debt securities, and finally caused the freezing of liquid resources and the upheaval of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft deal was overthrown by a group of Republican MPs last week.
It seems that we have managed to get out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed that certain “poisoning” assets of companies in difficulty will only be provided by the government rather than acquiring them.
In order to ensure that all members of Congress are satisfied, the plan also included a provision that requires that if the government has to bear the losses under the program for five years, it may levy new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a instalment of USD 250 billion would be paid first, followed by an additional USD 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of the remaining 350 billion dollars should be approved by Congress with another vote.
In exchange for the assistance, Washington acquires a stake in the supported companies, through which he receives dividends from the profits and can sell after the crisis has passed.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of real estate that will cover mortgages involved in the plan. It may also set maximum wages and severance payments to managers of the companies affected by the crisis.
The drafters of the plan would like the plan to be voted on by the House of Representatives today and the Senate on Wednesday.
However, despite their efforts, it is still not certain that the plan will be approved.
Yesterday, the statements against the plan were repeated again among both Republicans and Democrats.
“It’s clear that Washington won’t hear your voice,” said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House’s Finance Committee.
“Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is no one that would benefit taxpayers.”
Brad Sherman, the leader of the small congressional group called the “skeptic faction,” presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four of great economic experts, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us to ask Congress not to hurry and to thoroughly examine which path you will choose,” Sherman said.
At the same moment, they realized again in Europe that this is a global crisis.
Following a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalize part of the Fortis banking group in the amount of 11.2 billion euros (14.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French BNP Paribas announced that it would not buy its competitor on the verge of bankruptcy after it lost 2 million euros (USD 2.9 billion) due to the crisis in subprime mortgages in the United States.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the top 20 European banks and the top ten insurance companies.
“This is not a waste of money,” Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
“We have the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what depositors and households appreciate now that the situation promises to be insecure.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of La Manche, the British government seems to be planning to nationalize another bank that has been swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over the total amount of the ongoing loans from the Bradford and Bringley bank, of which real estate loans amount to 41 billion pounds (USD 75.5 billion).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they will acquire the British bank’s subsidiaries and customers.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of the crisis.
