According to a study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose out in a type of competition, such as eBay’s auction, so they pay too high a price.
The research was trying to map this "play" neurological scheme using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers took the lottery, the other group participated in a player auction, while using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method, they examined the active brain areas of the subjects.
Participants could win money in both games, but during the auction game, in which the overbiding of the other party is an essential element, the complex under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, became intensively activated when the game is lost.
This brain area, among many other functions, plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price can be explained by avoiding a violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theory, the economic members of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In it, three groups bid against a partner in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was and they made their bets.
In addition, another group was promised that if they were winning the game, they would receive 15 dollars in money as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, was paid just 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group lost the money in the event of a losing auction.
So the difference between the two groups was just that for one of them the win, and for the other the loss.
However, by proving the neurologist hypothesis, the members of the team playing against "loss" were willing to bets even higher than the control and "wins" group.
“These results cannot be derived from any existing economic theory.
So far, they have only explained the phenomena at the auction with the joy of victory and the avoidance of risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped resolve the contradiction between these two theories by now obtaining a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we go to the doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, the leading cause of death is the case with chronic liver disease.
The number of people with hepatitis in Hungary is estimated at 100,000, but only seven thousand are treated, which is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The term hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver prerogatives caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms have a lot of similarities, hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
The hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (intrade, vaginal secretion, saliva).
Travellers should be vaccinated against the A and B viruses, there is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal complaint, nausea.
After that, the jaundice can be seen on the skin and the white eye, the feces are light, the urine becomes dark, the healing can take up to two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die from a more severe type of disease, hepatitis B--derived liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people is infected with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can also lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, because the pathogen destroys the cells of the liver insidiously, in many cases the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent early prevention and regular screening tests.
In three groups, there are far more than average cases: people who had been through blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is estimated at 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is worth to consult the family doctor when any symptoms of unknown origin are detected.
Recognising the disease can be cured in time, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so that the infectivity can be eliminated and the development of cancer can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was held for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients around the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
