The flight of the bumblebee is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collision, if not the imitation of obstacle sensors in the natural world?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C bioi-imitation car robotic control system, a robotic minicar that has been endowed with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of promoting the design of a system that eliminates all collisions.
During flight, each bee forms its oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety shield, Kazuhhiro Doi, technology PR and R&D director, explained at the exhibition.
It is important to play the role of the complex eye of the uterus, which can be seen in all directions in a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the complex eye, the engineers used the idea of a laser telemeter.
In front of the BR23C, this identifies obstacles within a distance of two meters in a 180-degree field of vision, calculates their distance, and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid a collision.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is detected, and the car robot, immeiting the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to avoid the impact.
Unlike any current system, this avoidable maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If that wasn’t the case, the car robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
It must react in an exponently and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inseen layer of safety protection, a layer within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in a blink of an eye.
However, unlike the bees, the deviation should not be directed up, downwards or diagonally, only two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the swirability of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibility of avoiding other bees, only rotating motion and acceleration, as well as deceleration, were used as an option for the car robot.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means that they have a longer service life than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, an instinctive intelligent reaction is important, not the ability to process data, even less to store it.
This device has to process and respond to only a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No need for gigabytes of memory of the size of a megabyte.
This is the first step in developing an immediate evasion technology that Nissan estimates that will allow production cars to enter production cars within ten years.
Further application can be the assembly of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to drive the driver to the specified end destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
