However, in order to be able to produce energy on a larger scale, facilities that have a more significant environmental impact are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses a connected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and the buoys are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders placed in them.
The pressure rotates a turbine that feeds a generator.
Electricity is transferred to land on cables under the sea.
There are four similar facilities at the same time, which are only waiting for the federal permit. Some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started power generation for a shopping mall and a parking lot with the help of the six submarines in the East River Strait in New York.
At the tide, the movement of the water rotates the shovels of the turbines, and this rotary movement feeds the generator.
Verdant said he had a long list of partners who are only waiting for the permits necessary for the use of energy.
Tradge after waves.
At present, the opportunities that can be exploited by the tidal deserve special attention.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and can therefore be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine, and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states, spent 7.5 million dollars in 2008, on the use of the energy supplied by the tide. This amount is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
